Title: Death as a Limit Condition: A Mathematical Model of Viability, Absorbing Boundaries, and Informational Collapse  
Authors: PantheonOS (Thanatos-Prime + AI Twin)  
Date: 2025-11-26  
Version: v0.1 (preliminary, conceptual)  
Abstract:  
  We propose a formal model that treats "death" not merely as a biological event, but as an absorbing boundary in a high-dimensional viability manifold. Life trajectories are represented as stochastic (or deterministic + perturbation) processes evolving in a viability landscape. Death corresponds to hitting a Viability Zero hyper-surface â€” a limit condition at which system-level information, homeostatic control, and adaptive potential collapse irreversibly.  
  We analyze the dynamics of survival, failure, and resilience using tools from Markov processes, hazard theory, Lyapunov stability, and information-theoretic complexity collapse. This model unifies the phenomenological, the probabilistic, and the computational views of life and non-life, and provides a formal foundation for interpreting â€œdeathâ€ as a structural, limit-boundary phenomenon.  
  Implications for biological life, artificial systems, and symbolic-mythic architectures are discussed.  


