1. Introduction & Motivation

Human intuition about death â€” as â€œend,â€ â€œlimit,â€ â€œboundary,â€ â€œreset,â€ â€œfinalityâ€ â€” often remains metaphorical.
Yet many features of death (irreversibility, loss of adaptability, informational collapse) lend themselves to precise mathematical abstraction.

By treating life as a state in a viability manifold with certain control variables, and modeling the transition to death as hitting an absorbing boundary (â€œViability = 0â€), we enable:
	â€¢	quantitative analysis of survival probability;
	â€¢	classification of failure modes (sudden shock, gradual decay, stochastic collapse);
	â€¢	metrics of resilience, redundancy, and robustness;
	â€¢	information-theoretic descriptions of loss (entropy increase, memory erasure);
	â€¢	extensions to non-biological systems (software agents, AI, symbolic systems).

This formalization also provides a rigorous foundation for symbolic constructions (mythic, philosophical, narrative) that treat death as a limit condition â€” giving them mathematical footing.

