2. Definitions & Formal Setup

2.1 Viability Space and State Vector

Let
\mathbf{x}(t) \in \mathbb{R}^n
be the â€œstate vectorâ€ of an organism/system at time t, capturing all relevant variables: metabolic state, structural integrity, information content, homeostatic parameters, etc.

Define a viability function
V: \mathbb{R}^n \;\to\; \mathbb{R}_{\ge 0}
such that:
	â€¢	V(\mathbf{x}) > 0 â†” system is viable (life).
	â€¢	V(\mathbf{x}) = 0 â†” absorbing death boundary (non-viability).

Assume V(\mathbf{x}) is continuous.

Define the viability manifold
\mathcal{M} = \{ \mathbf{x} \mid V(\mathbf{x}) > 0 \}
and the death boundary
\partial \mathcal{M} = \{ \mathbf{x} \mid V(\mathbf{x}) = 0 \}

2.2 Dynamics: State Evolution

We model evolution of state as:

Option A â€” Stochastic differential equation (SDE):
d\mathbf{x} = f(\mathbf{x})\, dt + G(\mathbf{x})\, d\mathbf{W}(t)
with drift f (deterministic physiology/repair dynamics), and noise term G (environmental perturbations, stochastic stress).

Option B â€” Discrete-time Markov chain (for abstract agents):
\mathbf{x}_{t+1} = M(\mathbf{x}_t, \eta_t)
with random perturbation \eta_t.

Define the hitting time
T = \inf \{ t \mid \mathbf{x}(t) \in \partial \mathcal{M} \}
Death occurs when T is finite.

