3. Survival, Hazard, and Expected Lifetime

3.1 Survival Function and Hazard Rate

Let
S(t) = \Pr[ T > t ]
be the survival function. The hazard rate (instantaneous risk of death) is:

h(t) = -\frac{d}{dt} \ln S(t)

Under the SDE model, using Fokker-Planck or Kolmogorov forward equations, one can â€” in principle â€” compute S(t) given drift, diffusion, and boundary geometry.

3.2 Mean Lifetime and Resilience Metrics

Define mean lifetime:

\mathbb{E}[T] = \int_0^{\infty} S(t)\, dt

Resilience metrics:
	â€¢	Margin-to-death: \inf_{\tau < t} V(\mathbf{x}(\tau)) over a time horizon.
	â€¢	Redundancy coefficient: measure of state-space redundancy against perturbations (higher dimension, more orthogonal stability subspaces).
	â€¢	Entropy capacity: information-theoretic measure of the systemâ€™s representation and repair capacity.

