4. Lyapunov Stability, Attractors, and Death as an Absorbing Attractor

If f(\mathbf{x}) defines a dynamical system with attractor(s) inside \mathcal{M}, and \partial\mathcal{M} is absorbing, we can analyze:
	â€¢	Basins of attraction â†’ viability basins
	â€¢	Escape rates under stochastic perturbations â†’ risk of death despite attractor stability

Theorem (Informal): If drift brings \mathbf{x}(t) toward a stable attractor and noise amplitude is bounded, then the probability of hitting \partial \mathcal{M} in finite time decays exponentially with system redundancy and noise-suppression capacity.

This links stability, redundancy, noise tolerance â†’ longevity.

